1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:08,375
When you're running a live event as a director,

2
00:00:08,675 --> 00:00:10,675
your eyes are everywhere.

3
00:00:10,975 --> 00:00:13,975
You're watching the session list, the broadcast bar,

4
00:00:14,275 --> 00:00:16,900
the delay strip, the operator presence indicators.

5
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:19,450
Somewhere in the middle of that,

6
00:00:19,750 --> 00:00:23,500
you also need to know what's actually happening on stage

7
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:28,675
at this exact moment — without having to hunt for the session card.

8
00:00:28,975 --> 00:00:31,975
That's what the Stage Confidence Monitor is for.

9
00:00:32,275 --> 00:00:35,650
One click and your entire screen becomes a single,

10
00:00:35,950 --> 00:00:38,575
giant, impossible-to-miss display of the current session.

11
00:00:38,875 --> 00:00:40,875
Let me show you.

12
00:00:41,175 --> 00:00:44,925
In the context panel on the right side of the

13
00:00:45,225 --> 00:00:47,850
director console — the same panel that

14
00:00:48,150 --> 00:00:50,400
shows your quick action buttons —

15
00:00:50,700 --> 00:00:52,950
scroll down to the Monitor section.

16
00:00:53,250 --> 00:00:57,750
You'll see a button labeled 'Stage Monitor' with a little screen icon.

17
00:00:58,050 --> 00:01:00,050
Click it.

18
00:01:00,350 --> 00:01:02,600
The overlay fills the entire screen.

19
00:01:02,900 --> 00:01:05,900
This is not a new browser window or

20
00:01:06,200 --> 00:01:09,575
a new tab — it's a fixed overlay that

21
00:01:09,875 --> 00:01:13,1000
sits on top of the production console at z-index nine thousand.

22
00:01:14,300 --> 00:01:16,550
Your console is still running underneath,

23
00:01:16,850 --> 00:01:19,475
all your realtime subscriptions are still live,

24
00:01:19,775 --> 00:01:22,025
you haven't navigated away from anything.

25
00:01:22,325 --> 00:01:26,075
At the top: the live session status in red —

26
00:01:26,375 --> 00:01:29,750
a pulsing dot and the words 'YOU ARE LIVE'.

27
00:01:30,050 --> 00:01:33,800
In the centre: the session title in massive type —

28
00:01:34,100 --> 00:01:37,100
responsive, so it scales with your screen size.

29
00:01:37,400 --> 00:01:40,400
Up to eighty pixels on a large display.

30
00:01:40,700 --> 00:01:42,700
Below that, the speaker's name.

31
00:01:42,1000 --> 00:01:44,1000
Below that: the timer.

32
00:01:45,300 --> 00:01:47,925
A large monospaced countdown showing minutes and

33
00:01:48,225 --> 00:01:51,225
seconds remaining — the exact same clock that

34
00:01:51,525 --> 00:01:54,525
drives the timer cards in the session list,

35
00:01:54,825 --> 00:01:58,200
synced to the server via CueDeck's clock offset mechanism.

36
00:01:58,500 --> 00:02:02,250
At the bottom of the centre section: the next session.

37
00:02:02,550 --> 00:02:05,175
Title, speaker, room, scheduled start time —

38
00:02:05,475 --> 00:02:08,850
everything the director needs to think one step ahead.

39
00:02:09,150 --> 00:02:12,900
And in a thin footer bar at the very bottom:

40
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:15,450
the live clock on the right,

41
00:02:15,750 --> 00:02:17,1000
the event name on the left.

42
00:02:18,300 --> 00:02:22,050
The timer on the stage monitor uses the same three-colour

43
00:02:22,350 --> 00:02:24,600
scheme you'll see everywhere in CueDeck.

44
00:02:24,900 --> 00:02:28,275
Green: the session has more than five minutes remaining.

45
00:02:28,575 --> 00:02:30,575
You're in good shape.

46
00:02:30,875 --> 00:02:33,500
The label below the timer says 'REMAINING'.

47
00:02:33,800 --> 00:02:35,800
Amber: under five minutes left.

48
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:38,725
The timer colour shifts to amber and

49
00:02:39,025 --> 00:02:41,275
the label changes to 'WRAPPING UP'.

50
00:02:41,575 --> 00:02:45,325
This is your nudge to start thinking about the transition.

51
00:02:45,625 --> 00:02:47,625
Red: under two minutes.

52
00:02:47,925 --> 00:02:49,925
The label becomes 'ENDING NOW'.

53
00:02:50,225 --> 00:02:54,350
Time to get ready to call the next session to stage.

54
00:02:54,650 --> 00:02:57,275
If the session goes into OVERRUN —

55
00:02:57,575 --> 00:02:59,825
past its scheduled end time —

56
00:03:00,125 --> 00:03:03,500
the timer flips to show a positive number and

57
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:05,800
the label changes to 'OVERTIME'.

58
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:10,975
The timer counts upward, telling you exactly how far over time you are.

59
00:03:11,275 --> 00:03:13,900
These thresholds are the same five-minute and

60
00:03:14,200 --> 00:03:17,200
two-minute marks used in the session cards and

61
00:03:17,500 --> 00:03:19,750
the stage timer display mode —

62
00:03:20,050 --> 00:03:23,050
the whole system speaks the same visual language.

63
00:03:23,350 --> 00:03:27,100
In practice, the Stage Confidence Monitor is for a very

64
00:03:27,400 --> 00:03:31,150
specific moment: when the director needs to be physically watching

65
00:03:31,450 --> 00:03:33,700
something else — the stage door,

66
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:37,750
the operator feed, a conversation with the venue manager —

67
00:03:38,050 --> 00:03:41,800
but still needs peripheral awareness of the current session state.

68
00:03:42,100 --> 00:03:45,475
You pop it open on a secondary monitor or

69
00:03:45,775 --> 00:03:49,525
a dedicated screen, and you never have to dig through

70
00:03:49,825 --> 00:03:53,575
the session list to answer 'how much time does the

71
00:03:53,875 --> 00:03:55,875
current speaker have left'.

72
00:03:56,175 --> 00:03:59,175
It's right there, full screen, two metres away.

73
00:03:59,475 --> 00:04:02,100
It also syncs immediately with state changes.

74
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:06,150
The moment you or another director transitions the session —

75
00:04:06,450 --> 00:04:09,450
ENDED, HOLD, OVERRUN — the stage monitor updates.

76
00:04:09,750 --> 00:04:11,750
No delay, no refresh.

77
00:04:12,050 --> 00:04:15,425
The live session switches, the next session moves up,

78
00:04:15,725 --> 00:04:18,725
and the timer resets for the new context.

79
00:04:19,025 --> 00:04:22,775
The stage monitor isn't only useful when something is LIVE.

80
00:04:23,075 --> 00:04:25,325
When a session is READY or

81
00:04:25,625 --> 00:04:29,000
CALLING — meaning it's been flagged to start but

82
00:04:29,300 --> 00:04:33,425
hasn't gone live yet — the monitor shows a different state.

83
00:04:33,725 --> 00:04:36,725
The status line changes to 'STANDING BY —

84
00:04:37,025 --> 00:04:39,025
STARTING SHORTLY' in amber.

85
00:04:39,325 --> 00:04:41,575
The title and speaker are shown.

86
00:04:41,875 --> 00:04:45,625
The timer shows the scheduled start time rather than a

87
00:04:45,925 --> 00:04:48,175
countdown, and the colour is amber.

88
00:04:48,475 --> 00:04:51,850
And if there's genuinely nothing active at all —

89
00:04:52,150 --> 00:04:55,900
between events, or before the first session of the day

90
00:04:56,200 --> 00:04:59,575
— the monitor shows 'STANDBY' with the event name,

91
00:04:59,875 --> 00:05:02,500
and the next session details below it.

92
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:04,800
You still have context.

93
00:05:05,100 --> 00:05:07,725
You're never looking at a blank screen.

94
00:05:08,025 --> 00:05:11,775
To close the monitor, hit the small 'CLOSE' button in

95
00:05:12,075 --> 00:05:14,700
the top right corner of the overlay.

96
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:17,000
That's it.

97
00:05:17,300 --> 00:05:21,050
Your console comes back exactly as you left it —

98
00:05:21,350 --> 00:05:23,350
nothing reloaded, no state lost.

99
00:05:23,650 --> 00:05:25,900
You can also press Escape —

100
00:05:26,200 --> 00:05:29,950
the keyboard handler recognises Escape as a dismiss for overlays,

101
00:05:30,250 --> 00:05:32,250
so it works here too.

102
00:05:32,550 --> 00:05:34,550
Stage Monitor isn't director-only.

103
00:05:34,850 --> 00:05:38,600
The AV role and the signage role also have access

104
00:05:38,900 --> 00:05:42,275
to the Stage Monitor button in their context panel.

105
00:05:42,575 --> 00:05:46,325
The AV team can open it to keep track of

106
00:05:46,625 --> 00:05:49,625
what's live while they're managing their equipment feeds.

107
00:05:49,925 --> 00:05:54,800
The signage operator can use it to coordinate timing for manual override actions.

108
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:58,100
Stage and registration roles don't have the button,

109
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:02,525
because their views already surface what they need at a glance.

110
00:06:02,825 --> 00:06:06,575
But any role that benefits from a dedicated confidence display

111
00:06:06,875 --> 00:06:08,875
has access to it.

112
00:06:09,175 --> 00:06:11,175
Simple feature, high value.

113
00:06:11,475 --> 00:06:13,475
One button, full-screen context.

114
00:06:13,775 --> 00:06:17,525
The monitor pulls from the same live data as everything

115
00:06:17,825 --> 00:06:21,575
else in CueDeck — it's not a separate system or

116
00:06:21,875 --> 00:06:26,000
a separate subscription, just a different view on the same state.

117
00:06:26,300 --> 00:06:30,050
In the next episode we move from this director-facing display

118
00:06:30,350 --> 00:06:34,100
to something the speaker themselves looks at: the Stage Timer.

119
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:38,150
That's a full-screen countdown designed to sit on a monitor

120
00:06:38,450 --> 00:06:40,700
or tablet facing the stage —

121
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,125
so the presenter always knows exactly how much time they have.

122
00:06:45,425 --> 00:06:47,425
See you there.
